<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-415-319  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 415 319.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 17 1990 v7 n37 p159(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ask Computer Systems purchases troubled Ingres. (database makerIngres Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burke, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   ASK Computer Systems Inc. (acquisitions and mergers)Ingres Corp. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Ticker:    ASKI; RELY.andO;Topic:     AcquisitionFinancial StabilityData base management systemsSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Ask Computer Systems Purchases Troubled IngresandM;Ask Computer Systems Inc., a manufacturing software maker, is acquiringfinancially strapped database maker Ingres Corp. for $110 million with helpfrom industry giants Electronic Data Systems Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co.andM;To fund the purchase, Ask, of Mountain View, Calif., sold 20 percent of itsstock to systems integrator Electronic Data Systems and 10 percent tocomputer maker Hewlett-Packard, for a total of $60 million in cash.andM;Ask will come up with another $30 million from its own pocket and will getthe remaining $20 million from a bank loan, according to Ask spokeswomanKaren Marvin.andM;The deal thrusts Ask into the troubled database market.andP;  The 10-year-oldIngres, whose earnings were down $6.1 million for the last fiscal year to$76,000, is one of several database manufacturers being squeezed by asluggish market.andP;  (See Oracle story, above.)andM;Oracle Corp., Ingres' rival, will face stiffer competition because of thedeal, analysts said.andP;  &quot;Ingres is now a much tougher competitor,&quot; said RichardFinkelstein, president of Performance Computing Inc., a Chicago databaseconsulting firm.andM;Under the agreement, Ingres will be come a wholly owned subsidiary of Ask.andO;Ingres President Paul Newton plans to step down after the acquisition iscompleted, Ingres officials said.andM;Ingres had been looking for a cash infusion for the last nine months.andP;  It hadagreed to sell a stake to Digital Equipment Corp., but the negotationscollapsed in June.andM;&quot;With [delays in] getting our new products out, we created problems forourselves,&quot; said Ray Carvey, treasurer for Ingres, which is based in Alameda,Calif.andP;  &quot;That affected our revenue stream and reduced profitability, and thenpeople started worrying about our financial viability.&quot;andM;Ingres stock was up 65 percent after the deal was announced, to $9 on Sept.andO;12.andP;  However, it's not all good news for Ingres: The firm may faceconsolidation and cutbacks.andP;  Carvey said the extent of the cutbacks should beknown by October.andM;Ask has 930 employees and finished its fiscal year in June with $207 millionin sales.andP;  Ingres, which has 1,200 employees, finished its fiscal year inJune with $157 million in sales.andO;</TEXT></DOC>